# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baldwin-apple
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The **Great September Gale of 1815** was a deadly and fast-moving Category 4 Atlantic hurricane in 1815 that became the second of five known major hurricanes to strike New England.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] At the time, it was the first hurricane to strike the greater area in 180 years.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] After striking on Long Island, the hurricane caused major damage in Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Hampshire and Rhode Island.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] Rhode Island suffered the worst damage, as the storm surge flooded towns along Narragansett Bay up to and including Providence.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The summer of 1815 was reported to have been unusually stormy, possibly because of transient climate changes induced by ash clouds from the eruption of Mount Tambora in April.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The hurricane first struck the Turks Islands near the Bahamas on September 20, with a strength estimated to have been equivalent to a Category 4 hurricane.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The storm struck Long Island on September 23, 1815, probably coming ashore near Center Moriches around 7:00 A.M.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] On the south shore of Long Island it broke through the barrier beach and created the inlet that still isolates Long Beach, which had previously been an eastward extension of The Rockaways.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] Around 9:00 A.M. the storm came ashore at Saybrook, Connecticut with the force of what would now be considered a Category 3 hurricane.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] Waves of up to six feet were reported in New London.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The "Great Storm" (or "Great Gale"), as it was known there, hit Providence, Rhode Island on the morning of September 23.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] From about 10:00 A.M. to noon, the storm delivered a storm surge that funneled up Narragansett Bay where it destroyed some 500 houses and 35 ships.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] Dozens of ships were deposited on the streets of Providence.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The bowsprit of the ship "Ganges" was smashed into the third story of the Washington Insurance Company building.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The Second Baptist Meeting House was destroyed.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] Most of the buildings on the east side from south of the Market House to India Point were destroyed.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] At India Point, houses and wharves were destroyed.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] Both the Washington Bridge and the Central (Red) Bridge were uprooted from their piers and destroyed.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The rain appears to have been saturated with salt.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The leaves on trees which were not blown away were covered with a white salt coating that resembled a light frost.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] A line on the Old Market Building marks the 11-foot (3.4 m) storm surge that was unsurpassed in the city until the 1938 New England hurricane, which brought a 17.6-foot (5.4 m) storm surge.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] There is still a worn plaque on the Rhode Island Hospital Trust building (built in 1917), along with a newer plaque showing the higher 1938 hurricane water level.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] At Matunuck, Rhode Island, sediment studies have identified the overwash fan of sediments in Succotash Marsh, where the 1815 hurricane storm surge overtopped the barrier beach.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The financial loss was estimated at one and a half million dollars, one-quarter the total valuation of the city.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] Fortunately, only two people died, both in India Point.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] After the storm, much of the Narragansett Bay area was rebuilt with higher riverbanks, raised wharves, and more durable building practices, to help protect against future storms.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] In Dorchester, Massachusetts, just south of Boston, local historian William Dana Orcutt wrote in the late 19th century of the hurricane's impact: "In 1815 there was a great gale which destroyed the arch of the bridge over the Neponset River.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] This arch was erected over the bridge at the dividing line of the towns [Dorchester and Milton] in 1798." Dorchester's First Parish Meeting House was too badly damaged to repair.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] The eye passed into New Hampshire near Jaffrey and Hillsborough.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] In the aftermath of the Great Gale, the concept of a hurricane as a "moving vortex" was presented by John Farrar, Hollis Professor of Mathematics and Natural Philosophy at Harvard University.
[src:baldwin-apple/1815-new-england-hurricane] In an 1819 paper he concluded that the storm "appears to have been a moving vortex and not the rushing forward of a great body of the atmosphere".
[src:baldwin-apple/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:baldwin-apple/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:baldwin-apple/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:baldwin-apple/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:baldwin-apple/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:baldwin-apple/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:baldwin-apple/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:baldwin-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:baldwin-apple/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:baldwin-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:baldwin-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:baldwin-apple/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:baldwin-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:baldwin-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:baldwin-apple/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:baldwin-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:baldwin-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:baldwin-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:baldwin-apple/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:baldwin-apple/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:baldwin-apple/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:baldwin-apple/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:baldwin-apple/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:baldwin-apple/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:baldwin-apple/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:baldwin-apple/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:baldwin-apple/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:baldwin-apple/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] The **Baldwin apple** is a bright red winter apple, very good in quality, and easily shipped.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] It was for many years the most popular apple in New England, New York, and for export from the United States of America.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] No apple in the vicinity of Boston was so popular as Baldwin.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] It has also been known as 'Calville Butter', 'Felch', 'Late Baldwin', 'Pecker', 'Red Baldwin's Pippin', 'Steele's Red Winter', and 'Woodpecker'.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] The Baldwin was one of four apples honored by the United States Postal Service in a 2013 set of four 33¢ stamps commemorating historic strains, joined by Northern Spy, Golden Delicious, and Granny Smith.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] According to local tradition, the apple was found near Wood Hill by William Butters (1711-1784), grandson of Will Butter, first white settler in what is now Wilmington, Massachusetts.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] William Butters raised the tree in his yard on the Butters Farm, near the present Baldwin Apple Monument *(pictured)*.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Beach's *Apples of New York*, the Baldwin originated soon after 1740 as a chance seedling on the farm of Mr.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] John Ball of Wilmington, Massachusetts, and for about 40 years thereafter its cultivation was confined to that immediate neighborhood.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] The farm later came into the possession of a Mr.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Butters, who gave the name *Woodpecker* to the apple because the tree was frequented by woodpeckers.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Deacon Samuel Thompson, a surveyor of Woburn, Massachusetts, brought it to the attention of Col.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Loammi Baldwin, who propagated it and more widely introduced it in eastern Massachusetts.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Baldwin's interest in the variety it came to be called the Baldwin.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] A monument to the Baldwin apple now stands on today's Chestnut street in Wilmington.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] The monument's inscription reads: *This monument marks the site of the first Baldwin Apple Tree found growing wild near here.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] The apple first known as the Butters, Woodpecker or Pecker apple was named after Col.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] A harsh winter in 1934 wiped out many of the Baldwin apple orchards in New England.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Its popularity as an eating apple waned, but some orchards were preserved for many years because of its desirability as a mixing apple for cider.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] However, the orchards have not been replaced when they played out.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Baldwin Apples, unlike many apples, have long been prized for the making of hard cider.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] "West County Cider" makes Baldwin Cider from trees planted in the early 1900s.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] It is an exceptionally hard apple and would remain remarkably free from blemishes and other blights with few pesticides being needed.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Because of its hardness it shipped well without bruising and for a time was prized for this quality.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Aside from cider making it was also known as an exceptionally good pie apple and due to its inherent hardness would maintain more crispness through the baking process than other apples would.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Essex County, New Jersey, in the time of the Dutch, was also well known for its apple groves and cider, connected with the Bauldwin family.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Baldwins were once the most popular apples in the United States, but have largely fallen out of existence with the introduction of the Red Delicious.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] While not extinct, they are very difficult to find in stores.
[src:baldwin-apple/baldwin-apple] Some trees can still be found wild in abandoned orchards in New England, notably in Vermont.
